# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: singer-taps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:singer-taps/blob-readme-md] Singer is an open source standard for moving data between databases, web APIs, files, queues, and just about anything else you can think of.
[src:singer-taps/blob-readme-md] The Singer spec describes how data extraction scripts — called “Taps” — and data loading scripts — called “Targets” — should communicate using a standard JSON-based data format over stdout.
[src:singer-taps/blob-readme-md] By conforming to this spec, Taps and Targets can be used in any combination to move data from any source to any destination.
[src:singer-taps/blob-readme-md] Join the Singer Slack channel to get help from members of the Singer community.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The decision to integrate data tends to arise when the volume, complexity (that is, big data) and need to share existing data explodes.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] It has become the focus of extensive theoretical work, and numerous open problems remain unsolved.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Data integration encourages collaboration between internal as well as external users.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The data being integrated must be received from a heterogeneous database system and transformed to a single coherent data store that provides synchronous data across a network of files for clients.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] A common use of data integration is in data mining when analyzing and extracting information from existing databases that can be useful for Business information.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Issues with combining heterogeneous data sources, often referred to as information silos, under a single query interface have existed for some time.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In the early 1980s, computer scientists began designing systems for interoperability of heterogeneous databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The first data integration system driven by structured metadata was designed in 1991 at the University of Minnesota for the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] IPUMS used a data warehousing approach, which extracts, transforms, and loads data from heterogeneous sources into a unique view schema so data from different sources become compatible.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] By making thousands of population databases interoperable, IPUMS demonstrated the feasibility of large-scale data integration.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The data warehouse approach offers a tightly coupled architecture because the data are already physically reconciled in a single queryable repository, so it usually takes little time to resolve queries.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The data warehouse approach is less feasible for data sets that are frequently updated, requiring the extract, transform, load (ETL) process to be continuously re-executed for synchronization.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Difficulties also arise in constructing data warehouses when one has only a query interface to summary data sources and no access to the full data.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This problem frequently emerges when integrating several commercial query services like travel or classified advertisement web applications.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] A trend began in 2009 favoring the loose coupling of data and providing a unified query-interface to access real time data over a mediated schema (see Figure 2), which allows information to be retrieved directly from original databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This is consistent with the SOA approach popular in that era.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This approach relies on mappings between the mediated schema and the schema of original sources, and translating a query into decomposed queries to match the schema of the original databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Such mappings can be specified in two ways: as a mapping from entities in the mediated schema to entities in the original sources (the "Global-as-View" (GAV) approach), or as a mapping from entities in the original sources to the mediated schema (the "Local-as-View" (LAV) approach).
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The latter approach requires more sophisticated inferences to resolve a query on the mediated schema, but makes it easier to add new data sources to a (stable) mediated schema.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] As of 2010, some of the work in data integration research concerns the semantic integration problem.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This problem addresses not the structuring of the architecture of the integration, but how to resolve semantic conflicts between heterogeneous data sources.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] For example, if two companies merge their databases, certain concepts and definitions in their respective schemas like "earnings" inevitably have different meanings.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In one database it may mean profits in dollars (a floating-point number), while in the other it might represent the number of sales (an integer).
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] A common strategy for the resolution of such problems involves the use of ontologies which explicitly define schema terms and thus help to resolve semantic conflicts.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This approach represents ontology-based data integration.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] On the other hand, the problem of combining research results from different bioinformatics repositories requires bench-marking of the similarities, computed from different data sources, on a single criterion such as positive predictive value.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This enables the data sources to be directly comparable and can be integrated even when the natures of experiments are distinct.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] As of 2011, it was determined that current data modeling methods were imparting data isolation into every data architecture in the form of islands of disparate data and information silos.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This data isolation is an unintended artifact of the data modeling methodology that results in the development of disparate data models.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Disparate data models, when instantiated as databases, form disparate databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Enhanced data model methodologies have been developed to eliminate the data isolation artifact and to promote the development of integrated data models.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] One enhanced data modeling method recasts data models by augmenting them with structural metadata in the form of standardized data entities.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] As a result of recasting multiple data models, the set of recast data models will now share one or more commonality relationships that relate the structural metadata now common to these data models.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Commonality relationships are a peer-to-peer type of entity relationships that relate the standardized data entities of multiple data models.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Multiple data models that contain the same standard data entity may participate in the same commonality relationship.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] When integrated data models are instantiated as databases and are properly populated from a common set of master data, then these databases are integrated.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Since 2011, data hub approaches have been of greater interest than fully structured (typically relational) Enterprise Data Warehouses.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Since 2013, data lake approaches have risen to the level of Data Hubs.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] (See all three search terms popularity on Google Trends.) These approaches combine unstructured or varied data into one location, but do not necessarily require an (often complex) master relational schema to structure and define all data in the Hub.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Data integration plays a big role in business regarding data collection used for studying the market.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Converting the raw data retrieved from consumers into coherent data is something businesses try to do when considering what steps they should take next.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Organizations are more frequently using data mining for collecting information and patterns from their databases, and this process helps them develop new business strategies to increase business performance and perform economic analyses more efficiently.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Compiling the large amount of data they collect to be stored in their system is a form of data integration adapted for Business intelligence to improve their chances of success.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Consider a web application where a user can query a variety of information about cities (such as crime statistics, weather, hotels, demographics, etc.).
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Traditionally, the information must be stored in a single database with a single schema.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] But any single enterprise would find information of this breadth somewhat difficult and expensive to collect.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Even if the resources exist to gather the data, it would likely duplicate data in existing crime databases, weather websites, and census data.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] A data-integration solution may address this problem by considering these external resources as materialized views over a virtual mediated schema, resulting in "virtual data integration".
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This means application-developers construct a virtual schema—the *mediated schema*—to best model the kinds of answers their users want.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Next, they design "wrappers" or adapters for each data source, such as the crime database and weather website.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] These adapters simply transform the local query results (those returned by the respective websites or databases) into an easily processed form for the data integration solution (see figure 2).
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] When an application-user queries the mediated schema, the data-integration solution transforms this query into appropriate queries over the respective data sources.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Finally, the virtual database combines the results of these queries into the answer to the user's query.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This solution offers the convenience of adding new sources by simply constructing an adapter or an application software blade for them.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] It contrasts with ETL systems or with a single database solution, which require manual integration of entire new data set into the system.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The virtual ETL solutions leverage virtual mediated schema to implement data harmonization; whereby the data are copied from the designated "master" source to the defined targets, field by field.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Advanced data virtualization is also built on the concept of object-oriented modeling in order to construct virtual mediated schema or virtual metadata repository, using hub and spoke architecture.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Each data source is disparate and as such is not designed to support reliable joins between data sources.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Therefore, data virtualization as well as data federation depends upon accidental data commonality to support combining data and information from disparate data sets.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Because of the lack of data value commonality across data sources, the return set may be inaccurate, incomplete, and impossible to validate.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] One solution is to recast disparate databases to integrate these databases without the need for ETL.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The recast databases support commonality constraints where referential integrity may be enforced between databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The recast databases provide designed data access paths with data value commonality across databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The theory of data integration forms a subset of database theory and formalizes the underlying concepts of the problem in first-order logic.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Applying the theories gives indications as to the feasibility and difficulty of data integration.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] While its definitions may appear abstract, they have sufficient generality to accommodate all manner of integration systems, including those that include nested relational / XML databases and those that treat databases as programs.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Connections to particular databases systems such as Oracle or DB2 are provided by implementation-level technologies such as JDBC and are not studied at the theoretical level.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Data integration systems are formally defined as a tuple $\left\langle G,S,M\right\rangle$ where G is the global (or mediated) schema, S is the heterogeneous set of source schemas, and M is the mapping that maps queries between the source and the global schemas.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Both G and S are expressed in languages over alphabets composed of symbols for each of their respective relations.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The mapping M consists of assertions between queries over G and queries over S .
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] When users pose queries over the data integration system, they pose queries over G and the mapping then asserts connections between the elements in the global schema and the source schemas.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] A database over a schema is defined as a set of sets, one for each relation (in a relational database).
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The database corresponding to the source schema S would comprise the set of sets of tuples for each of the heterogeneous data sources and is called the *source database*.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Note that this single source database may actually represent a collection of disconnected databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The database corresponding to the virtual mediated schema G is called the *global database*.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The global database must satisfy the mapping M with respect to the source database.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The legality of this mapping depends on the nature of the correspondence between G and S .
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Two popular ways to model this correspondence exist: *Global as View* or GAV and *Local as View* or LAV.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] GAV systems model the global database as a set of views over S .
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of G a query over S .
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Query processing becomes a straightforward operation due to the well-defined associations between G and S .
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The burden of complexity falls on implementing mediator code instructing the data integration system exactly how to retrieve elements from the source databases.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] If any new sources join the system, considerable effort may be necessary to update the mediator, thus the GAV approach appears preferable when the sources seem unlikely to change.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In a GAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer would first develop mediators for each of the city information sources and then design the global schema around these mediators.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] For example, consider if one of the sources served a weather website.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The designer would likely then add a corresponding element for weather to the global schema.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Then the bulk of effort concentrates on writing the proper mediator code that will transform predicates on weather into a query over the weather website.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This effort can become complex if some other source also relates to weather, because the designer may need to write code to properly combine the results from the two sources.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] On the other hand, in LAV, the source database is modeled as a set of views over G .
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In this case M associates to each element of S a query over G .
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Here the exact associations between G and S are no longer well-defined.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] As is illustrated in the next section, the burden of determining how to retrieve elements from the sources is placed on the query processor.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The benefit of an LAV modeling is that new sources can be added with far less work than in a GAV system, thus the LAV approach should be favored in cases where the mediated schema is less stable or likely to change.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In an LAV approach to the example data integration system above, the system designer designs the global schema first and then simply inputs the schemas of the respective city information sources.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Consider again if one of the sources serves a weather website.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The designer would add corresponding elements for weather to the global schema only if none existed already.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Then programmers write an adapter or wrapper for the website and add a schema description of the website's results to the source schemas.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The complexity of adding the new source moves from the designer to the query processor.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The theory of query processing in data integration systems is commonly expressed using conjunctive queries and Datalog, a purely declarative logic programming language.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] One can loosely think of a conjunctive query as a logical function applied to the relations of a database such as " $f(A,B)$ where $A<B$ ".
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] If a tuple or set of tuples is substituted into the rule and satisfies it (makes it true), then we consider that tuple as part of the set of answers in the query.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] While formal languages like Datalog express these queries concisely and without ambiguity, common SQL queries count as conjunctive queries as well.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In terms of data integration, "query containment" represents an important property of conjunctive queries.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] A query A contains another query B (denoted $A\supset B$ ) if the results of applying B are a subset of the results of applying A for any database.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The two queries are said to be equivalent if the resulting sets are equal for any database.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This is important because in both GAV and LAV systems, a user poses conjunctive queries over a *virtual* schema represented by a set of views, or "materialized" conjunctive queries.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Integration seeks to rewrite the queries represented by the views to make their results equivalent or maximally contained by our user's query.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This corresponds to the problem of answering queries using views (AQUV).
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In GAV systems, a system designer writes mediator code to define the query-rewriting.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Each element in the user's query corresponds to a substitution rule just as each element in the global schema corresponds to a query over the source.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Query processing simply expands the subgoals of the user's query according to the rule specified in the mediator and thus the resulting query is likely to be equivalent.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] While the designer does the majority of the work beforehand, some GAV systems such as Tsimmis involve simplifying the mediator description process.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In LAV systems, queries undergo a more radical process of rewriting because no mediator exists to align the user's query with a simple expansion strategy.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The integration system must execute a search over the space of possible queries in order to find the best rewrite.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The resulting rewrite may not be an equivalent query but maximally contained, and the resulting tuples may be incomplete.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] As of 2011 the GQR algorithm is the leading query rewriting algorithm for LAV data integration systems.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] In general, the complexity of query rewriting is NP-complete.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] If the space of rewrites is relatively small, this does not pose a problem — even for integration systems with hundreds of sources.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] Large-scale questions in science, such as real world evidence, global warming, invasive species spread, and resource depletion, are increasingly requiring the collection of disparate data sets for meta-analysis.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] This type of data integration is especially challenging for ecological and environmental data because metadata standards are not agreed upon and there are many different data types produced in these fields.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] National Science Foundation initiatives such as Datanet are intended to make data integration easier for scientists by providing cyberinfrastructure and setting standards.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The Research Data Alliance, has more recently explored creating global data integration frameworks.
[src:singer-taps/data-integration] The OpenPHACTS project, funded through the European Union Innovative Medicines Initiative, built a drug discovery platform by linking datasets from providers such as European Bioinformatics Institute, Royal Society of Chemistry, UniProt, WikiPathways and DrugBank.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A properly designed ETL system extracts data from source systems and enforces data type and data validity standards and ensures it conforms structurally to the requirements of the output.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems can also deliver data in a presentation-ready format so that application developers can build applications and end users can make decisions.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The ETL process is often used in data warehousing.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL systems commonly integrate data from multiple applications (systems), typically developed and supported by different vendors or hosted on separate computer hardware.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The separate systems containing the original data are frequently managed and operated by different stakeholders.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] For example, a cost accounting system may combine data from payroll, sales, and purchasing.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL and its variant ELT (extract, load, transform), are increasingly used in cloud-based data warehousing.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Applications involve not only batch processing, but also real-time streaming.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL processing involves extracting the data from the source system(s).
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] In many cases, this represents the most important aspect of ETL, since extracting data correctly sets the stage for the success of subsequent processes.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Most data-warehousing projects combine data from different source systems.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Each separate system may also use a different data organization and/or format.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The streaming of the extracted data source and loading on-the-fly to the destination database is another way of performing ETL when no intermediate data storage is required.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] An intrinsic part of the extraction involves data validation to confirm whether the data pulled from the sources has the correct/expected values in a given domain (such as a pattern/default or list of values).
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] If the data fails the validation rules, it is rejected entirely or in part.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The rejected data is ideally reported back to the source system for further analysis to identify and to rectify incorrect records or perform data wrangling.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] In the data transformation stage, a series of rules or functions are applied to the extracted data in order to prepare it for loading into the end target.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] An important function of transformation is data cleansing, which aims to pass only "proper" data to the target.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The challenge when different systems interact is in the relevant systems' interfacing and communicating.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Character sets that may be available in one system may not be in others.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The load phase loads the data into the end target, which can be any data store including a simple delimited flat file or a data warehouse.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Depending on the requirements of the organization, this process varies widely.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Some data warehouses may overwrite existing information with cumulative information; updating extracted data is frequently done on a daily, weekly, or monthly basis.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Other data warehouses (or even other parts of the same data warehouse) may add new data in a historical form at regular intervals – for example, hourly.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] To understand this, consider a data warehouse that is required to maintain sales records of the last year.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] This data warehouse overwrites any data older than a year with newer data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] However, the entry of data for any one year window is made in a historical manner.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The timing and scope to replace or append are strategic design choices dependent on the time available and the business needs.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] More complex systems can maintain a history and audit trail of all changes to the data loaded in the data warehouse.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] As the load phase interacts with a database, the constraints defined in the database schema – as well as in triggers activated upon data load – apply (for example, uniqueness, referential integrity, mandatory fields), which also contribute to the overall data quality performance of the ETL process.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Audit reports (for example, on compliance with business rules.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Archive (Extreme, space-efficient compression for very rarely used, old data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL processes can involve considerable complexity, and significant operational problems can occur with improperly designed ETL systems.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The range of data values or data quality in an operational system may exceed the expectations of designers at the time validation and transformation rules are specified.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Data profiling of a source during data analysis can identify the data conditions that must be managed by transform rules specifications, leading to an amendment of validation rules explicitly and implicitly implemented in the ETL process.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Data warehouses are typically assembled from a variety of data sources with different formats and purposes.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] As such, ETL is a key process to bring all the data together in a standard, homogeneous environment.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Design analysis should establish the scalability of an ETL system across the lifetime of its usage – including understanding the volumes of data that must be processed within service level agreements.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The time available to extract from source systems may change, which may mean the same amount of data may have to be processed in less time.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Some ETL systems have to scale to process terabytes of data to update data warehouses with tens of terabytes of data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Increasing volumes of data may require designs that can scale from daily batch to multiple-day micro batch to integration with message queues or real-time change-data-capture for continuous transformation and update.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Unique keys play an important part in all relational databases, as they tie everything together.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A unique key is a column that identifies a given entity, whereas a foreign key is a column in another table that refers to a primary key.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Keys can comprise several columns, in which case they are composite keys.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] In many cases, the primary key is an auto-generated integer that has no meaning for the business entity being represented, but solely exists for the purpose of the relational database – commonly referred to as a surrogate key.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] As there is usually more than one data source getting loaded into the warehouse, the keys are an important concern to be addressed.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] For example: customers might be represented in several data sources, with their Social Security number as the primary key in one source, their phone number in another, and a surrogate in the third.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Yet a data warehouse may require the consolidation of all the customer information into one dimension.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A recommended way to deal with the concern involves adding a warehouse surrogate key, which is used as a foreign key from the fact table.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Usually, updates occur to a dimension's source data, which must be reflected in the data warehouse.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] If the primary key of the source data is required for reporting, the dimension already contains that piece of information for each row.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] If the source data uses a surrogate key, the warehouse must keep track of it even though it is never used in queries or reports; it is done by creating a lookup table that contains the warehouse surrogate key and the originating key.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] This way, the dimension is not polluted with surrogates from various source systems, while the ability to update is preserved.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The lookup table is used in different ways depending on the nature of the source data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A new dimension row is added with the new state of the source system, while the previous dimension row is updated to reflect it is no longer active and time of deactivation.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL vendors benchmark their record-systems at multiple TB (terabytes) per hour (or ~1 GB per second) using powerful servers with multiple CPUs, multiple hard drives, multiple gigabit-network connections, and much memory.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] In real life, the slowest part of an ETL process usually occurs in the database load phase.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Databases may perform slowly because they have to take care of concurrency, integrity maintenance, and indices.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Still, even using bulk operations, database access is usually the bottleneck in the ETL process.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Whether to do certain operations in the database or outside may involve a trade-off.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] For example, removing duplicates using `distinct` may be slow in the database; thus, it makes sense to do it outside.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] On the other side, if using `distinct` significantly (x100) decreases the number of rows to be extracted, then it makes sense to remove duplications as early as possible in the database before unloading data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A common source of problems in ETL is a big number of dependencies among ETL jobs.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] For example, job "B" cannot start while job "A" is not finished.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] One can usually achieve better performance by visualizing all processes on a graph, and trying to reduce the graph making maximum use of parallelism, and making "chains" of consecutive processing as short as possible.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Again, partitioning of big tables and their indices can really help.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Another common issue occurs when the data are spread among several databases, and processing is done in those databases sequentially.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Sometimes database replication may be involved as a method of copying data between databases – it can significantly slow down the whole process.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] This approach allows processing to take maximum advantage of parallelism.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] For example, if you need to load data into two databases, you can run the loads in parallel (instead of loading into the first – and then replicating into the second).
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Sometimes processing must take place sequentially.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] For example, dimensional (reference) data are needed before one can get and validate the rows for main "fact" tables.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Some ETL software implementations include parallel processing.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] This enables a number of methods to improve overall performance of ETL when dealing with large volumes of data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] All three types of parallelism usually operate combined in a single job or task.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] An additional difficulty comes with making sure that the data being uploaded is relatively consistent.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Because multiple source databases may have different update cycles (some may be updated every few minutes, while others may take days or weeks), an ETL system may be required to hold back certain data until all sources are synchronized.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Likewise, where a warehouse may have to be reconciled to the contents in a source system or with the general ledger, establishing synchronization and reconciliation points becomes necessary.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Data warehousing procedures usually subdivide a big ETL process into smaller pieces running sequentially or in parallel.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] To keep track of data flows, it makes sense to tag each data row with "row_id", and tag each piece of the process with "run_id".
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] In case of a failure, having these IDs help to roll back and rerun the failed piece.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Best practice also calls for *checkpoints*, which are states when certain phases of the process are completed.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Once at a checkpoint, it is a good idea to write everything to disk, clean out some temporary files, log the state, etc.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] An established ETL framework may improve connectivity and scalability.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A good ETL tool must be able to communicate with the many different relational databases and read the various file formats used throughout an organization.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL tools have started to migrate into enterprise application integration, or even enterprise service bus, systems that now cover much more than just the extraction, transformation, and loading of data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Many ETL vendors now have data profiling, data quality, and metadata capabilities.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A common use case for ETL tools include converting CSV files to formats readable by relational databases.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] A typical translation of millions of records is facilitated by ETL tools that enable users to input CSV-like data feeds/files and import them into a database with as little code as possible.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL tools are typically used by a broad range of professionals – from students in computer science looking to quickly import large data sets to database architects in charge of company account management, ETL tools have become a convenient tool that can be relied on to get maximum performance.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL tools in most cases contain a GUI that helps users conveniently transform data, using a visual data mapper, as opposed to writing large programs to parse files and modify data types.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] While ETL tools have traditionally been for developers and IT staff, research firm Gartner wrote that the new trend is to provide these capabilities to business users so they can themselves create connections and data integrations when needed, rather than going to the IT staff.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Gartner refers to these non-technical users as Citizen Integrators.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] In online transaction processing (OLTP) applications, changes from individual OLTP instances are detected and logged into a snapshot, or batch, of updates.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] An ETL instance can be used to periodically collect all of these batches, transform them into a common format, and load them into a data lake or warehouse.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Data virtualization can be used to advance ETL processing.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The application of data virtualization to ETL allowed solving the most common ETL tasks of data migration and application integration for multiple dispersed data sources.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Virtual ETL operates with the abstracted representation of the objects or entities gathered from the variety of relational, semi-structured, and unstructured data sources.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] ETL tools can leverage object-oriented modeling and work with entities' representations persistently stored in a centrally located hub-and-spoke architecture.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Such a collection that contains representations of the entities or objects gathered from the data sources for ETL processing is called a metadata repository and it can reside in memory or be made persistent.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] By using a persistent metadata repository, ETL tools can transition from one-time projects to persistent middleware, performing data harmonization and data profiling consistently and in near-real time.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Extract, load, transform (ELT) is a variant of ETL where the extracted data is loaded into the target system first.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] The architecture for the analytics pipeline shall also consider where to cleanse and enrich data as well as how to conform dimensions.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to more easily handle both unstructured and structured data.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Ralph Kimball and Joe Caserta's book *The Data Warehouse ETL Toolkit*, (Wiley, 2004), which is used as a textbook for courses teaching ETL processes in data warehousing, addressed this issue.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Cloud-based data warehouses like Amazon Redshift, Google BigQuery, Microsoft Azure Synapse Analytics, and Snowflake provide highly scalable computing power.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] This lets businesses forgo preload transformations and replicate raw data into their data warehouses, where it can transform them as needed using SQL.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] After having used ELT, data may be processed further and stored in a data mart.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Most data integration tools skew towards ETL, while ELT is popular in database and data warehouse appliances.
[src:singer-taps/extract-transform-load] Similarly, it is possible to perform TEL (Transform, Extract, Load) where data is first transformed on a blockchain (as a way of recording changes to data, e.g., token burning) before extracting and loading into another data store.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:singer-taps/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:singer-taps/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:singer-taps/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:singer-taps/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:singer-taps/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:singer-taps/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:singer-taps/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:singer-taps/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:singer-taps/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:singer-taps/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:singer-taps/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:singer-taps/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:singer-taps/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:singer-taps/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:singer-taps/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:singer-taps/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:singer-taps/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:singer-taps/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:singer-taps/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:singer-taps/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:singer-taps/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:singer-taps/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:singer-taps/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:singer-taps/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:singer-taps/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:singer-taps/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:singer-taps/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:singer-taps/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:singer-taps/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:singer-taps/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:singer-taps/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:singer-taps/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:singer-taps/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:singer-taps/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:singer-taps/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:singer-taps/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:singer-taps/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:singer-taps/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:singer-taps/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:singer-taps/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:singer-taps/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:singer-taps/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:singer-taps/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:singer-taps/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:singer-taps/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:singer-taps/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:singer-taps/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:singer-taps/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:singer-taps/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:singer-taps/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:singer-taps/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:singer-taps/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:singer-taps/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:singer-taps/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:singer-taps/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:singer-taps/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:singer-taps/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:singer-taps/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:singer-taps/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:singer-taps/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:singer-taps/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:singer-taps/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:singer-taps/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:singer-taps/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:singer-taps/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:singer-taps/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:singer-taps/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:singer-taps/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:singer-taps/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:singer-taps/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:singer-taps/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:singer-taps/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:singer-taps/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:singer-taps/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:singer-taps/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:singer-taps/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:singer-taps/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:singer-taps/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:singer-taps/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:singer-taps/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:singer-taps/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:singer-taps/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:singer-taps/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:singer-taps/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:singer-taps/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:singer-taps/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:singer-taps/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] In software engineering, a **pipeline** consists of a chain of processing elements (processes, threads, coroutines, functions, *etc.*), arranged so that the output of each element is the input of the next.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] The concept is analogous to a physical pipeline.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Usually some amount of buffering is provided between consecutive elements.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] The information that flows in these pipelines is often a stream of records, bytes, or bits, and the elements of a pipeline may be called filters.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This is also called the **pipe(s) and filters** design pattern which is monolithic.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Its advantages are simplicity and low cost while its disadvantages are lack of elasticity, fault tolerance and scalability.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Connecting elements into a pipeline is analogous to function composition.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Narrowly speaking, a pipeline is linear and one-directional, though sometimes the term is applied to more general flows.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] For example, a primarily one-directional pipeline may have some communication in the other direction, known as a *return channel* or *backchannel,* as in the lexer hack, or a pipeline may be fully bi-directional.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Flows with one-directional trees and directed acyclic graph topologies behave similarly to linear pipelines.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] The lack of cycles in such flows makes them simple, and thus they may be loosely referred to as "pipelines".
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Pipelines are often implemented in a multitasking OS, by launching all elements at the same time as processes, and automatically servicing the data read requests by each process with the data written by the upstream process.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This can be called a *multiprocessed pipeline.* In this way, the scheduler will naturally switch the CPU among the processes so as to minimize its idle time.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] In other common models, elements are implemented as lightweight threads or as coroutines to reduce the OS overhead often involved with processes.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Depending on the OS, threads may be scheduled directly by the OS or by a thread manager.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Coroutines are always scheduled by a coroutine manager of some form.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Read and write requests are usually blocking operations.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This means that the execution of the source process, upon writing, is suspended until all data can be written to the destination process.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Likewise, the execution of the destination process, upon reading, is suspended until at least some of the requested data can be obtained from the source process.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This cannot lead to a deadlock, where both processes would wait indefinitely for each other to respond, since at least one of the processes will soon have its request serviced by the operating system, and continue to run.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] For performance, most operating systems implementing pipes use pipe buffers, which allow the source process to provide more data than the destination process is currently able or willing to receive.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Under most Unixes and Unix-like operating systems, a special command is also available, typically called "buffer", that implements a pipe buffer of potentially much larger and configurable size.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This command can be useful if the destination process is significantly slower than the source process, but it is desired that the source process complete its task as soon as possible.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] E.g., if the source process consists of a command which reads an audio track from a CD and the destination process consists of a command which compresses the waveform audio data to a format like MP3.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] In this case, buffering the entire track in a pipe buffer would allow the CD drive to spin down more quickly, and enable the user to remove the CD from the drive before the encoding process has finished.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Such a buffer command can be implemented using system calls for reading and writing data.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Wasteful busy waiting can be avoided by using facilities such as poll or select or multithreading.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] CMS Pipelines is a port of the pipeline idea to VM/CMS and z/OS systems.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] It supports much more complex pipeline structures than Unix shells, with steps taking multiple input streams and producing multiple output streams.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] (Such functionality is supported by the Unix kernel, but few programs use it as it makes for complicated syntax and blocking modes, although some shells do support it via arbitrary file descriptor assignment).
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Traditional application programs on IBM mainframe operating systems have no standard input and output streams to allow redirection or piping.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Instead of spawning processes with external programs, CMS Pipelines features a lightweight dispatcher to concurrently execute instances of more than 200 built-in programs that implement typical UNIX utilities and interface to devices and operating system services.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] In addition to the built-in programs, CMS Pipelines defines a framework to allow user-written REXX programs with input and output streams that can be used in the pipeline.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Data on IBM mainframes typically resides in a record-oriented filesystem and connected I/O devices operate in record mode rather than stream mode.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] As a consequence, data in CMS Pipelines is handled in record mode.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] For text files, a record holds one line of text.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] In general, CMS Pipelines does not buffer the data but passes records of data in a lock-step fashion from one program to the next.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This ensures a deterministic flow of data through a network of interconnected pipelines.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Beside byte stream-based pipelines, there are also object pipelines.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] In an object pipeline, processing elements output objects instead of text.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] PowerShell includes an internal object pipeline that transfers .NET objects between functions within the PowerShell runtime.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Channels, found in the Limbo programming language, are other examples of this metaphor.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Graphical environments such as RISC OS and ROX Desktop also use pipelines.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Rather than providing a save dialog box containing a file manager to let the user specify where a program should write data, RISC OS and ROX provide a save dialog box containing an icon (and a field to specify the name).
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] The destination is specified by dragging and dropping the icon.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] The user can drop the icon anywhere an already-saved file could be dropped, including onto icons of other programs.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] If the icon is dropped onto a program's icon, it is loaded and the contents that would otherwise have been saved are passed in on the new program's standard input stream.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] For instance, a user browsing the world-wide web might come across a .gz compressed image which they want to edit and re-upload.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Using GUI pipelines, they could drag the link to their de-archiving program, drag the icon representing the extracted contents to their image editor, edit it, open the save as dialog, and drag its icon to their uploading software.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Conceptually, this method could be used with a conventional save dialog box, but this would require the user's programs to have an obvious and easily accessible location in the filesystem.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] As this is often not the case, GUI pipelines are rare.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] The name "pipeline" comes from a rough analogy with physical plumbing in that a pipeline usually allows information to flow in only one direction, like water often flows in a pipe.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] Pipes and filters can be viewed as a form of functional programming, using byte streams as data objects.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] More specifically, they can be seen as a particular form of monad for I/O.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] The concept of pipeline is also central to the Cocoon web development framework or to any XProc (the W3C Standards) implementations, where it allows a source stream to be modified before eventual display.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This pattern encourages the use of text streams as the input and output of programs.
[src:singer-taps/pipeline-software] This reliance on text has to be accounted when creating graphic shells to text programs.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The Singer Specification is an open source standard for defining the format of data exchange.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The standard is useful because it enables Data Professionals to move data between arbritrary systems as long as the programs generating and ingesting the data can understand this format.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This documentation is our attempt at simplifying the canonical specification into an easier to understand and follow format for people who are new to the Singer community.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The full specification is in the Singer project on GitHub.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The current version of the spec is 0.3.0 and is versioned using Semantic Versioning.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The full specification for data exchange consists of three types of JSON-formatted messages: `schema`, `record`, and `state`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The `record` message contains the actual data being communicated, the `schema` message defines the structure of the data, and the `state` message keeps track of the progress of an extraction.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Each `record` message contains a `stream` identifier which specifies the unique name of that data.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] For data coming from an API this can be thought of as the name of the endpoint.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] For data coming from a database this might be the table name.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The `schema` message will have a matching `stream` identifier for the records it describes.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The term "stream" will be used in the rest of the documentation to identify a set of data being extracted.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] These 3 message types are generated by programs called `taps`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] A tap can be written in any programming language (note that Meltano will only run Python-based taps).
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Taps output the 3 messages to standard output, aka `stdout`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Taps are required to accept 1 file, called a configuration (`config`) file, and can optionally accept 2 other files called `state` and `catalog` files.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The 3 message types are consumed by programs called `targets`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] A target can be written in any programming language (note that Meltano will only run Python-based targets).
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Targets ingest the 3 messages from standard input, aka `stdin`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Targets can optionally accept a configuration file if the target system requires authentication information.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] For a simple target like a csv file, this would not be required, but for a more complicated target like a SaaS database, the config file would be required.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Since taps and targets are able to communicate to each other via the Singer spec, they can be used together to move data between systems.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This can be done on the command line by sending the messages from a tap to a target using a Unix pipe, `|`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] A pipe takes information from `stdout` of one process, in this case a tap, and redirects it to `stdin` of a second process, in this case a target.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This composability means taps and targets can be composed as simply as `tap | target`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Each of the messages have a defined schema and some required and optional fields.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Note that while example messages will be shown on multiple lines, each record when output from a tap must be on its own line.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Record messages contain the actual data being extracted from a source system.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Note that in the above example the message was formatted for readibility, but when output from a tap the entire message will be on a single-line.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Schema messages define the structure of the data sent in a record message.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] A JSON Schema is a way to annotate and validate JSON objects.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The data types available in raw JSON are limited compared to the variety of types available in many targets.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Within the Singer Spec, JSON schema definitions are used to tell a target the exact data type to use when storing data.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This definition now explicitly defines what kind of data is expected in a record and how to handle it when loading the data.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Also of note, there are several different versions of JSON Schema.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The most common one is Draft 4 and Meltano and the SDK both support this draft.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Note that in the above example the message was formatted for readability, but when output from a tap the entire message will be on a single-line.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Before any record messages for a given data stream are output by a tap, they must be preceded by a schema message for the stream.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] While the extraction will still work, it will be assumed that the record is schema-less and will be loaded in a potentially unexpected manner.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] State messages contain any information that a tap is designed to persist.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] These are used to inform the target of the current place in the extraction of a data stream.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] There structure of the `value` property is not defined by the spec and is determined by each tap independently.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The `bookmarks` key should be familiar since it's an optional key in a schema message.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Each property within the `bookmarks` JSON object is a data stream from a previously defined schema and record.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Each stream maps to a JSON object storing the last data point seen in the extraction.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] In the above example, the `tools` stream has extracted data up to the timestamp shown in the `updated_at` field.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Similarly, the `team` stream has extracted up to `id` = 123.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] When taps are run, they can accept three files that provide information necessary for it to work properly: config, state, and catalog files.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Taps are required to accept the config file, and can optionally accept the state and catalog files.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The config file contains the parameters required by the tap to succesfully extract data from the source.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Typically this will include credentials for an API or database connection.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Taps can optionally use a state file to start replication from a previous point in a data stream.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The structure of the state file and the state message described previously should be nearly identical.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] The `value` property in the state message will be the contents of any state.json file passed to a tap.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Catalog files define the structure of one or many data streams.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Taps are capable of both using and generating catalog files.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Discovery mode is how taps can generate catalogs.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] When a tap is invoked with a `--discover` it will output the full catalog list of streams available for extraction to `stdout`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This can then be saved to a `catalog.json` file.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Note that some older taps use `properties.json` as the catalog file.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Metadata is the preferred method of associating extra information about streams and properties within a stream.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] A tap can periodically emit structured log messages containing metrics about read operations.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Consumers of the tap logs can parse these metrics out of the logs for monitoring or analysis.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Here are some examples of metrics and how those metrics should be interpreted.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This can be interpreted as: an HTTP request to an "orders" endpoint was made that took 1.23 seconds and succeeded with a status code of 200.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This can be interpreted as: an HTTP request to an "orders" endpoint was made that took 30.01 seconds and failed with a status code of 500.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This can be interpreted as: a total of 314 records were fetched from an "orders" endpoint.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Metrics messages are interspersed with the primary 3 messages, so parsing them should be handled programmatically.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] When targets are run, they can accept a single config file that provides the information necessary for it to work properly.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Similar to taps, targets take a configuration file.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] There is no specification for the structure of a config file, as long as it is JSON based.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Unlike taps, targets do not take a state file.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] Targets are expected to read in the state messages from `stdin`, but typically they do not do anything with the state messages beyond sending them to `stdout`.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] This is done once all data that appeared in the stream before the state message has been processed by the Target.
[src:singer-taps/singer-spec] However, they are expected to read the schema messages from `stdin` and perform validation of the incoming record using the provided schema.
[src:singer-taps/www-singer-io] Singer powers data extraction and consolidation for all of your organization’s tools.
[src:singer-taps/www-singer-io] Singer describes how data extraction scripts—called “taps” —and data loading scripts—called “targets”— should communicate, allowing them to be used in any combination to move data from any source to any destination.
[src:singer-taps/www-singer-io] Send data between databases, web APIs, files, queues, and just about anything else you can think of.
[src:singer-taps/www-singer-io] Check out the directory of taps and targets for more data sources and destinations.
[src:singer-taps/www-singer-io] Join us on Slack to collaborate with hundreds of members of the Singer community.
[src:singer-taps/www-singer-io] Check out the Singer GitHub to learn more and see what projects are in the works.
